Rating: 4
Shortly after the oven door closed, the sweet aroma of garlic and olive oil danced throughout my home. I had all my other ingredients prepared and ready to go by the time the garlic was ready. For the non-roasted cloves, I used store-bought peeled whole clove garlic. (I cook a LOT of garlic dishes, so I wasn't concerned about any lack of freshness here). I also added 1 medium diced shallot to the recipe. The soup cooked up very easily and you could almost leave the cream out if you like, since once you puree it the soup does have a nice consistency thanks to the roasted garlic. I elected to use the cream though. For final seasoning, I added just a few grinds of black pepper, any additional saltiness I would leave at the diner's discretion, the parmesan would be plenty. The soup was a wonderful ballet of delicate flavor balanced with a silky texture that finessed every tastebud with its simple elegance. The lemon wedge does serve to brighten the dish perfectly. I reserve a "perfect" rating in any dish for that rare gem that is destined to become a staple in my kitchen. This dish earns that prestige. Not only does it deliver on simplicity of ingredients, ease of preparation, and excellent flavor, but the versatility is nearly endless. It could easily be turned into a fondue, a sauce (alfredo anyone?), even a braising or poaching liquid, and can be served as an accompaniment to nearly any dish I can imagine. This is truly a diamond of the kitchen. I will make this dish again soon, ready for another aromatic ballet of simple cooking elegance.

